<!-- I -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="header">
        <!-- <div class="number-wrapper">1</div> -->
        <h3>I kind of want to start freestyling, but...</h3>
        <h4>Protecting your mental health with a safe environment</h4>
      </div>
      <div class="text">
        <div class="p-header">Find a group to freestyle with</div>
        <p>If you take only one thing away from this guide, this needs to be it. Not having a group to freestyle with is the number one reason you're not freestyling. It's also the reason you tell yourself you're going to freestyle, but back out of the idea and proceed to play normally, or even dodge playing entirely, flushed with embarrassment for having considered something so ludicrous.</p>
        <div class="p-header">Why it’s important to freestyle with a group</div>
        <p>It's absolutely terrifying to be unnatural in public. It's only when you witness others being unnatural that the unnatural begins to seem natural, and you begin to feel comfortable engaging with it. It's for the same reason you might feel anime cons are a safe environment for you to enjoy your weird indulgences.</p>
        <p>Unfortunately, because most freestylers don't even freestyle in public, it's almost impossible to find a preconstructed freestyle group. It then falls to you to deceive yourself into believing that freestyle is the norm. You'll need to build a safe space for yourself by creating a group consisting of people equally interested in freestyle. The idea is to simulate a compact anime con environment to feel less afraid, less embarrassed, less awkward, and to reduce the impact from the disrespect you'll receive from onlookers.</p>
        <div class="p-header">When you create your group, ideally:</div>
        <ul>
          <li><span class="bp"></span>Your group consists of 2-3 others willing to improve or begin freestyle.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span>Your group consists of others who want to see you improve.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span>Your group consists of others who are at least generally okay as humans.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span>Your group does not consist of anyone who makes you or anyone else in your group feel inferior--whether it's because you're intimidated by their skill level, or because they're disrespectful or hurtful.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="p-header">If you are unable to find others to freestyle with:</div>
        <ul>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Try the <a href="https://twitter.com/FSTakeover" target="_blank">@FSTakeover</a> Discord.</span> That's pretty much <span class="italic">the</span> English-speaking freestyle community.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Definitely try freestyling on your own, but--</span> Recognize that there may come a point where you'll feel too awkward, terrified, or embarrassed to continue, and trying to push through the fear may not be healthy or worthwhile. But also recognize that this fear can be mitigated with a decent group, and that you shouldn't deny yourself the opportunity to try again if you manage to come across a setting that works for you.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">If your luck is incredible and you come across other freestylers in the wild,</span> you'll more than likely be welcome to join their session if you ask politely. The community is always excited to see new freestylers, and rejecting them is one of the most damaging things anyone can do to the community.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="p-header">If you're already freestyling without a group:</div>
        <p>Consider yourself fortunate to not have to deal with more intense levels of self-consciousness.</p>
      </div>

