    </div>
<!-- II -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="header">
        <!-- <div class="number-wrapper">1</div> -->
        <h3>Which difficulty do I choose?</h3>
        <h4>Prioritizing Beginner(DDR), Easy(DRS), and Whatever the Lowest Difficulty is Called on Pump(Pump)</h4>
      </div>
      <div class="text">
        <div class="p-header">Play on the lowest difficulty</div>
        <p>When you start freestyling, you might be immediately more comfortable with the guidance provided by higher difficulties--especially if you feel that you're more footwork-oriented--and doubly especially if you've been inspired by DRS shuffling videos--and triply especially if you've only ever been inspired by DDR and Pump freestyle videos of the 90s and early 2000s.</p>
        <div class="p-header">Ignore all that and play on the lowest difficulty.</div>
        <p>As difficulty lowers, game complexity decreases and game depth increases. On low difficulty, dance games are less about the hard numbers and more about the manifestation of your creativity, granting you with the open space required to find or be yourself.</p>

        <div class="p-header">My masculinity instructs me to believe that finding and being myself is nonsense
        and/or
        My Infatuation with 90s/00s Korean Freestylers is too powerful and I want to freestyle just like them and they play on higher difficulties and I believe I can become them by mimicking their difficulty selection
        and/or
        I wasn't born Japanese or Korean, but I definitely am both and I can prove it through my skill in gaming and we're known for being good at games so I'm going to be embarrassed if anyone catches me playing on low difficulty
        and/or
        I want some non-abstract reasons to freestyle on Beginner/Easy over other difficulties
        </div>
        <ul>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">It's significantly harder to fail:</span> One of the most awkward moments in freestyle is when the song abruptly ends during a performance and you feel your spectators judging you as you walk offstage. Reduce the possibility of failure and having to cope with that whole situation by playing on lower difficulties.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">fear less, smile more / Don't let yourself be too afraid of your lifebar:</span>
            By playing on lower difficulties, you can easily avoid feeling the unwanted tension and agitation that occurs as the entire screen begins blasting red at you. A flashing red screen pulls attention towards itself, and away from your performance. It changes the spectators' interest from the performance to whether the performer can survive to the end of the song.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Backwards compatibility:</span> On Beginner/Easy, you're free to perform the same footwork you'd perform on higher difficulties, but you're also given more freedom to deviate from footwork patterns you might find yourself falling back on. You can start applying any new techniques you learn instantly with the spaciousness lower difficulties provide.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Exercise musicality:</span> Dance games standardize the way in which you listen to music as their stepcharts generally follow either the kick or the melody. If a layer of the music not highlighted through stepcharts stands out to you, you'll have the freedom to capture and express that on Beginner/Easy without the friction you’d encounter from higher level stepcharts.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Go big:</span> Because you're less restricted to your side of the stage on lower difficulties, you're free to utilize the entire stage and experiment with larger, fuller motions.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Nobody's ever judged for their chart difficulty:</span> The majority of your audience cannot tell the difference between the lowest difficulty and the next difficulty up. And if you're putting on a performance, your spectators won't care what difficulty you're playing on. They'll take glances at the screen to determine whether you're really hitting the notes, but their main focus will be on you. Try to push past the thought of being judged for your difficulty selection. If spectators mock you, it won't be for chart difficulty.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

