        <!-- <div class="number-wrapper">1</div> -->
        <h3>I don't know what to do between notes/arrows/steps!</h3>
        <h4>Owning the music and becoming the protagonist</h4>
      </div>
      <div class="text">
        <div class="p-header">Notes don't dictate when to move, nor do they necessarily dictate how to move</div>
        <p>When you start freestyling on lower difficulties, you'll likely feel awkward during the gaps between notes. You might freeze up in uncertainty, or begin talking, or make awkward gestures in an attempt to communicate to your spectators that it's not your fault--that the game's the cause of this awkward moment. You might fear that your spectators feel awkward watching you await your next note--even if you have no spectators.</p>
        <p>There's no antidote for feeling this way, but you can prevent it. Freestyle is a moment about you. Avoid giving notes center stage by continuously performing through the gaps between them. Performing only when a note appears and halting performance where gaps exist changes the protagonist from you to the game--and that's not freestyling as much as it is playing tech with some flair.</p>

        <div class="p-header">If "Continuously perform through the gaps" is too nebulous, here are some things you can do between notes:</div>
        <ul>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Continue playing as if there are notes during the gaps:</span> Perform how you normally would if given a stream of notes to hit. Because these notes don't exist, you are free to apply your performance to parts of the stage you wouldn't normally touch.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Face the audience:</span> Even a quick spin during a gap between notes will grab the attention of your spectators. If you like the idea of momentarily facing the audience but are unable to commit to it, select a point in the distance before you begin your performance. Ignore the spectators and lock your eyes to your selected point whenever you decide to turn towards the spectators.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Move your arms with intent:</span> Bring contrast to your performance with upper body movement. With a lower note count, lower difficulties allow you to focus on creating expression with your arms during note gaps.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

