    </div>
<!-- IV -->
    <div class="section">
      <div class="header">
        <!-- <div class="number-wrapper">1</div> -->
        <h3>I don't know what to do with my arms!</h3>
        <h4>Utilizing your upper body and adding additional flair</h4>
      </div>
      <div class="text">
        <div class="p-header">It's very normal to be afraid of moving your arms</div>
        <p>It's surprising that many people still only consider freestyle to be rad footwork--but it's also understandable when taking into consideration "I don't know what to do with my arms" is a very common issue that's often answered with, "Do whatever you want!"
        This answer is so tremendously vague, many of the players told to "Do whatever you want" disregard it and never really bother to work arms into their performance.</p>
        <p>Because it's not standard procedure to utilize your arms during DDR/DRS/Pump outside of the two arm movements Proper Shufflers do, you will feel absolutely embarrassed
        moving your arms with purpose. Plus, it's just much easier to not give your arms any consideration, to hope it works out in the end, and to figure your arms probably look good anyway while doing the unintentional dangling backwards scoop.</p>

        <div class="p-header">Some starting points to get your arms feeling like they're part of your freestyle:</div>
        <ul>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Write your way out:</span> Before you start a song, think of a phrase. Write that phrase in the air while you perform. Note that the goal is not to finish writing your phrase before the song ends, but to feel comfortable using your arms. Take your time writing each character.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Object-oriented freestyling (OOF):</span> Think of an object before you start a song. Imagine that you're in possession of the object during the song. Imagine the different ways you can interact with the object, and recreate those interactions during your performance.</li>
          <li><span class="bp"></span><span class="strong">Call to Action:</span> Every 4-8 counts, a member of your group names an occupation. Embody the occupation during your performance, only breaking character once another occupation is named. If you're given "Knight," wield your sword, block incoming arrows, and die for your queen. If you're given "Ninja," attack twice, then dislocate your arms and run around the stage.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Be aware that these methods won't help with the embarrassment you'll definitely feel when you first engage your arms. That's just something that will dissipate over time.</p>
      </div>

